I feel that Neil's greatest strength is that he 'gets out of the 
ivory tower.' This is a leadership trait that some of the greatest
leaders in history have demonstrated. For example, Abraham Lincoln 
spent the majority of his time among his troops in order to gather 
the first hand knowledge needed to make informed, accurate and 
timely decisions. The typical union soldier enjoyed a bond with 
Lincoln that few people would ever have with a U.S. president.
Myself and many others enjoyed such a bond with Neil Novich, who 
sacrificed much of his personal time to get to know us personally 
and professionally. 
I have the greatest admiration for Neil. He is one of the most intelligent people I have ever met and is a brilliant strategist. Neil was very successful executing strategies to drive operational excellence, organic growth and improved customer satisfaction. These initiatives were effectively and concisely communicated so that all employees would understand the goals and could identify their action to meet them. The urgency to perform well was continuously reinforced and the organization continued to improve despite the immense challenges presented by conversion to SAP and ongoing consolidations resulting from acquisitions, most notably, Integris Metals which doubled 
the company's size.
