Neil S. Novich


What went right: In 2005, Mr. Novich engineered Ryerson's biggest acquisition ever by purchasing competitor Integris Metals Inc. of Minneapolis for $660 million. Ryerson was already the nation's largest steel distributor, but the deal doubled its revenues overnight.
Their strategy: Mr. Novich coveted Integris because of its market strength in aluminum and stainless steel, which fetch higher prices than carbon steel � Ryerson's primary product. The timing of the deal couldn't have been better. Prices for carbon steel, used to make cars and appliances, dropped in 2005, but "because Ryerson had more aluminum and stainless steel, it was able to post much higher results than people expected," says Timna Tanners, a steel industry analyst at UBS in New York.
Did it work? Ryerson's new product mix will make it less vulnerable to swings in steel prices, Ms. Tanners says. And because aluminum and stainless steel sell for $3,400 and $2,300 a ton vs. $640 a ton for carbon steel, the product mix will add to Ryerson's profit margins.




